{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535934"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.52,0.01,0.12,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61858"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8250"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19939"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61858"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of crampy lower abdominal pain, bloody diarrhoea, and 6 kg weight loss. He has no significant medical history apart from an appendicectomy five years ago. He does not take any regular medications. He does not smoke and drinks two standard drinks of alcohol per day. He returned from a working holiday in Nepal six weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 114/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with no localised tenderness. Digital rectal examination reveals blood-stained soft stool. Colonoscopy shows deep serpiginous ulcers with intervening normal mucosa in the transverse colon (Image). The rectum, remainder of the colon, and distal ileum appear normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ulcerative colitis","Crohn disease","Coeliac disease","Amoebiasis","Giardiasis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe colonoscopy findings of deep serpiginous ulcers with intervening normal mucosa creating a \u0027cobblestone\u0027 appearance are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E. The presence of skip lesions (areas of normal mucosa between affected areas) and the depth of ulceration are key distinguishing features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with continuous inflammation starting in the rectum and extending proximally. The colonoscopy would show diffuse erythema, friability, and superficial ulceration without skip lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the small intestine and would not cause the colonic changes seen here. Typical endoscopic findings include scalloping of duodenal folds and reduced duodenal fold height.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoebiasis\u003C/strong\u003E caused by \u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E can cause colitis with ulceration. While this should be considered given the travel history to Nepal, the classic flask-shaped ulcers and more diffuse colonic involvement would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiardiasis\u003C/strong\u003E caused by \u003Cem\u003EGiardia lamblia\u003C/em\u003E primarily affects the small intestine and does not cause colonic ulceration. While it can cause diarrhoea in returning travellers, the colonoscopic findings are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation with weight loss, bloody diarrhoea, and characteristic colonoscopic findings strongly supports the diagnosis of Crohn disease. While the travel history raises the possibility of infectious causes, the endoscopic appearance is diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Deep serpiginous ulcers with intervening normal mucosa (\u0027cobblestone\u0027 appearance) on colonoscopy is characteristic of Crohn disease","Skip lesions (areas of normal mucosa between affected areas) help differentiate Crohn disease from ulcerative colitis","Recent travel to endemic areas should raise suspicion for infectious causes of colitis"],"references":["Dolinger M, Torres J. Vermeire S. Crohn\u2019s disease. Lancet 2024 23; 403:1177-91."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15559"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21169"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21169"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Auj9yUJkkwIIPlystgzkWvdbrxahhX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Auj9yUJkkwIIPlystgzkWvdbrxahhX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":522,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47304"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T16:05:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-